\[ \text{Cramer's V} = \sqrt{\frac{\chi^2 / n }{\min\{r-1, c-1\}}}, \]

\(\chi^2\) - (X-squared), \(n\) - , \(r\) - , \(c\) - .

cramersV():

library(lsr)
cramersV(table(tivo))
## [1] 0.5888395

Cramers V 0 to 1.

:

\[ \chi^2 = \sum\limits_{i=1}^n\frac{(observed - expected)^2}{expected} \]

# by hand - for the sake of clarity
(18 - 17)^2 / 17 + (16 - 17)^2 / 17 + (1 - 5)^2 / 5 + (9 - 5)^2 / 5 + (6 - 3)^2 / 3 + (0 - 3)^2 / 3 
## [1] 12.51765
# using R tables - more convenient
sum((res$expected - res$observed) ** 2 / res$expected)

2:

vcd (from visualising categorical data).

#install.packages("vcd")
library(vcd)
mosaic(soc$phrase.eng ~ soc$moscow)

From this graph we can see that in Moscow people use (pickle) and (turkish drum) while teasing and people not from Moscow rarely use (turkish drum), but often say phrases with (pickle) and (chocolate bar). Now we will not focus on styling, later we will see how to create a mosaic plot via ggplot2, however, let us name axes in a more pretty way:

mosaic(data = soc, phrase.eng ~ moscow, 
       set_varnames = list(phrase.eng = "Phrase type", 
                           moscow = "Region of living"))

2x2, mosaicplot:

soc %>%
  mutate(pickle = ifelse(phrase.eng == "turkish drum", "drum", "not_drum")) %>%
  select(pickle,moscow) %>%
  table() %>%
  chisq.test()
## Warning in chisq.test(.): Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  .
## X-squared = 10.199, df = 1, p-value = 0.001405
soc %>%
  mutate(pickle = ifelse(phrase.eng == "turkish drum", "drum", "not_drum")) %>%
  select(pickle,moscow) %>%
  table() %>%
  mosaicplot(shade = TRUE)

heroes <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Pozdniakov/tidy_stats/master/data/heroes_information.csv",
                   na = c("-", "-99"))
## Warning: One or more parsing issues, call `problems()` on your data frame for details,

heroes %>%
  mutate(is_human = Race == "Human") %>%
  drop_na(is_human, Gender) %>%
  select(is_human, Gender) %>%
  table() %>%
  summary() #  or chisq.test(correct = FALSE) 
## Number of cases in table: 423 
## Number of factors: 2

##  Chisq = 0.0003745, df = 1, p-value = 0.9846
heroes %>%
  mutate(is_human = Race == "Human") %>%
  drop_na(is_human, Gender) %>%
  select(is_human, Gender) %>%
  table() %>%
